Tech CEOs on Trump
------------------

You don=E2=80=99t need me to tell you that there was grave politically-rela=
ted news in the U.S. over the weekend, as former President Trump survived a=
n assassination attempt; this isn=E2=80=99t a political site, and I don=E2=
=80=99t plan on becoming one now, but there was one tech angle that I thoug=
ht worth mentioning. From Business Insider ( https://www.businessinsider.co=
m/tech-ceos-business-leaders-react-trump-rally-shooting-2024-7 ) :

Prominent tech CEOs and billionaires condemned the shooting at a Trump rall=
y on Saturday, with some voicing their support for former President Donald =
Trump. At least two people, including the suspected shooter, were killed on=
 Saturday after shots were fired at the rally in Butler, Pennsylvania, acco=
rding to a statement from the Secret Service. Two other rally attendees wer=
e critically injured, the agency said. The shooting immediately drew reacti=
ons from top lawmakers, the Biden administration, and business leaders acro=
ss the political spectrum.

Here are the posts from the big 5 CEOs (the first four on X, in the inverse=
 order posted, while Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg posted on Threads):

I obviously echo their thoughts: I condemn all political violence, and exte=
nd my deepest sympathies to the family of the bystander who died.

It=E2=80=99s also notable, I think, not just that all of these CEOs comment=
ed, but also that those comments did seem appropriate: they are, in many re=
spects, in the small subset of people whose power and influence rivals that=
 of the president, and their constituents =E2=80=94 not just all Americans,=
 but nearly everyone in the world =E2=80=94 implicitly expected to hear fro=
m them on such a momentous occasion. It=E2=80=99s not nearly the most impor=
tant takeaway from this weekend, but a takeaway all the same.

X and the E.U.
--------------

From the Financial Times ( https://www.ft.com/content/9419e3b1-60ab-4bcb-a1=
ea-30cca911667a ) :

Elon Musk=E2=80=99s X is being threatened with hefty fines by the EU over t=
ransparency issues at the social media company, including allowing people t=
o acquire a =E2=80=9Ccheckmark=E2=80=9D once reserved for verified users. T=
he European Commission, the EU=E2=80=99s executive body, said on Friday tha=
t X was =E2=80=9Cin breach=E2=80=9D of the bloc=E2=80=99s Digital Services =
Act, which came into force this year and was designed to better police onli=
ne content.

In preliminary findings from an investigation that began last year, the EU =
said a decision following Musk=E2=80=99s $44bn takeover of the company two =
years ago, allowing anyone to pay to gain a blue checkmark, would deceive m=
illions of users. =E2=80=9CSince anyone can subscribe to obtain such a =E2=
=80=98verified=E2=80=99 status, it negatively affects users=E2=80=99 abilit=
y to make free and informed decisions about the authenticity of the account=
s and the content they interact with,=E2=80=9D said regulators in Brussels.=
 X can defend itself but if the EU=E2=80=99s findings are confirmed, the co=
mpany faces=C2=A0fines of up to 6 per cent of its total worldwide turnover.=
 In 2021, the last full year that Twitter published its revenues, the compa=
ny earned $5.1bn.

Commissioner for Internal Market Thierry Breton posted on X:

( https://twitter.com/ThierryBreton/status/1811699711591489637?ref_src=3Dtw=
