 (Eric Seufert told a similar story on X ( https://x.com/eric_seufert/statu=
s/1811721418394010084 ) ). Granted, I would like to think that I am trustwo=
rthy, but while blue checks were nominally for well-known people and journa=
lists, everyone knew it by-and-large came down to getting a favor from some=
 random Twitter employee; moreover, if there is one thing we have learned o=
ver the last decade it is that blue checks =E2=80=94 particularly to the ex=
tent they move in unison on controversial topics =E2=80=94 hardly have a mo=
nopoly on the truth.

Setting that aside, though, how is the decision of what labels to apply or =
not apply to various accounts the prerogative of E.U. bureaucrats? This is =
the very definition of government making product decisions, and not only is=
 that wrong in principle, it=E2=80=99s also totally unnecessary: the precip=
itating event for X=E2=80=99s dramatic fall-off in advertising revenue was =
the failed roll-out of the new blue-check system, when X allowed users to i=
mpersonate well-known brands like Nintendo ( https://kotaku.com/twitter-blu=
