Apple Settles with E.U. Over NFC
--------------------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-07-11/apple-a=
voids-eu-antitrust-threat-with-tap-and-pay-probe-settlement ) :

Apple Inc. has avoided the threat of fines from European Union regulators b=
y agreeing to open up its mobile wallet technology to other providers free =
of charge for a decade. The settlement brings to an end an investigation in=
to the US tech giant=E2=80=99s closely guarded payments technology. The EU =
earlier warned that restricting access to the technology amounted to an abu=
se of its market power.

=E2=80=9CApple has committed to allow rivals to access the =E2=80=98tap and=
 go=E2=80=99 technology of iPhones,=E2=80=9D the EU=E2=80=99s competition c=
hief Margrethe Vestager said. The decision will prevent Apple =E2=80=9Cfrom=
 excluding other mobile wallets from the iPhone=E2=80=99s ecosystem.=E2=80=
=9D Under the EU settlement, consumers in Europe will be able to use altern=
ative digital wallets to pay for goods and services at checkouts. The commi=
tments remain binding for 10 years and Apple risks a fine of as much as 10%=
 of global annual revenue if it violates the agreement.

As long as I=E2=80=99m on a streak of crushing the E.U.=E2=80=99s approach =
to regulating tech companies, it=E2=80=99s worth acknowledging points of ag=
reement =E2=80=94 and delineating why. In this case the E.U. is forcing App=
le to make an iPhone=E2=80=99s NFC capability available to 3rd parties; cri=
tically, the E.U. is not insisting that Apple does not create Apple Pay. In=
 other words, Apple can make its product better, but it also has to give a =
chance to developers; this is particularly important in terms of hardware a=
ccess, which is exactly what this settlement is about.

